properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall possible Monday and Monday night as a frontal system approaches with modified arctic air in place for the south coast. Modified arctic air will arrive over the south coast as a ridge of high pressure builds today. A frontal system will arrive over the south coast on Monday. The front combined with the modified arctic air in place will give potential to produce accumulating snow for neighbourhoods and roadways above 200 metres. In Howe Sound where colder air will reside, snow is expected to accumulate near sea level. The front will move out of the region Tuesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall amounts near 15 cm are forecast from this evening to Monday morning. A deep low will move across the Yukon this evening and move into the Northwest Territories Monday morning. Snow in advance of the system will reach the area this afternoon and continue through Monday morning. The snow will end later Monday as the system departs. A ridge of high pressure building quickly behind the system will bring gusty winds and local blowing snow on Monday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected today and tonight. A strong low pressure system from the Prairies will bring periods of freezing rain beginning this morning or early this afternoon. The freezing rain may intensify or become heavy tonight. The freezing rain will reach the Peawanuck area by late this afternoon or this evening. Freezing rain will taper off early on Monday morning. Ice accumulations of 5 to 10 mm are possible in some locations. Surfaces may become icy and slippery. ### Utility outages may occur. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A deep will move across the southern Dempster region this evening. It will be followed by a rapidly building ridge of high pressure from the Beaufort Sea tonight and Monday morning. As the ridge builds tonight, winds will increase to 80 km/h with gusts up to 100. The winds combined with freshly fallen snow will give blizzard conditions to the area. Conditions are forecast to improve during the day Monday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard developing Sunday for portions of southern Saskatchewan. Moderate to heavy snow associated with a powerful low pressure system began impacting southwestern Saskatchewan overnight. Snowfall totals as high as 30 to 50 cm are expected by Monday morning. Strong northerly winds will develop in the southwestern corner of the province this morning and spread eastwards through the day. These winds, along with with the heavy snow, will result in blizzard conditions. Conditions will remain extremely poor throughout the day and through the night before the system departs Monday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm continues. Moderate to heavy snow continues today over western and central Saskatchewan. A second potent winter storm will move into Saskatchewan today. This next system will spread an additional 10 to 20 cm of snow into The Battlefords northeastwards to Prince Albert by Monday morning. Accumulations from this second wave of snow will diminish rapidly towards the northwest. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A potent winter storm will bring heavy snow, wind, and a risk of freezing rain on Sunday. A powerful low pressure system will impact the Prairies today. Moderate to heavy snow will begin this morning and continue through to Monday. Snowfall totals as high as 30 to 50 cm are expected. Moderate northerly winds will develop and produce periods of reduced visibility in blowing snow today into Sunday night. Some regions will also see a mix of snow and freezing rain; consult local forecasts for more details on the location and timing. Conditions will remain extremely poor Sunday night before the system departs on Monday. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Ice build-up may cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2020-11-09T02:18:44-00:00

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain developing Sunday morning/afternoon and tapering off Sunday night. A powerful low pressure system will begin impacting the southern Prairies today and freezing rain will develop across portions of southeastern Saskatchewan and arc northeastwards across western Manitoba, through the northern Interlake, and into east-central Manitoba. The freezing rain will begin to taper off from west to east this evening and through the overnight. Ice accumulations from this band of freezing rain could exceed 5 mm. Some areas may see moderate northerly winds that, when combined with the accumulated ice, could cause damage to some above ground infrastructure and trees. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Ice build-up may cause tree branches to break. Utility outages may occur. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A wintry mix is expected beginning this evening. A strong low pressure system from the Prairies will bring snow mixed with ice pellets beginning early this evening. Snow and ice pellets may transition to or mix with freezing rain tonight and into Monday morning. Total snow and ice pellet amounts near 10 cm are possible by Monday morning. Surfaces may become icy and slippery. Take extra care when walking or driving in affected areas. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An intense weather system in the western high Arctic Islands is approaching Resolute Bay today. Strengthening southeasterly winds combined with falling snow are expected to produce blizzard conditions later this afternoon or evening. The blizzard conditions will persist through Monday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
